Types of Kubernetes Services
-----------------------------

ClusterIP
---------
Default type.
Accessible only inside the cluster.
Used for internal communication between microservices.



NodePort
--------
Exposes service on a static port on each node.
Accessible from outside using <NodeIP>:<NodePort>.



LoadBalancer
------------
Integrates with cloud provider to expose service externally with a public IP.



ExternalName
------------
Maps a service to an external DNS name.


**************************************************************
Basic Flow
Client sends request â†’ Service â†’ Selects Pod(s) â†’ Pod responds.
**************************************************************


Quick Notes & Tips
******************
Labels must match: Services route only to Pods matching their selector. Here both Services use app: myapp.
ClusterIP range: Allocated by Kubernetes and only reachable within the cluster.
NodePort range: Usually 30000â€“32767. If you omit nodePort, Kubernetes auto-assigns one.
Security: NodePort exposes your app on every node; consider network policies or an Ingress/LoadBalancer for production.

Troubleshooting:
kubectl describe svc myapp-nodeport -> to see endpoints.
kubectl get endpoints myapp-clusterip -> should list Pod IPs/ports; if empty, labels donâ€™t match or Pods arenâ€™t ready.




***********************************************************************************************

External Client â†’ NodeIP:31080 â†’ NodePort Service â†’ ClusterIP Service â†’ Pod:targetPort (80)


âœ… Meaning of the fields:

port (8888) â†’ The Serviceâ€™s internal port (ClusterIP). Other Pods use this inside the cluster.
targetPort (80) â†’ The actual port on the container inside the Pod.
nodePort (31080) â†’ The external port exposed on each node for outside access.


Inside the cluster, you can still use myapp-nodeport:8888 (DNS name) without worrying about node IPs.
Outside the cluster, you use NodeIP:31080.


